  ### **Hierarchical Synthesis**

* **Definition:** Retains RTL module boundaries**.**  
* **Flow:** Each module synthesized separately.

* **Advantages:**

  * Faster synthesis for large designs.  
  * Easier debugging (module structure preserved).

### **Flattened Synthesis**

* **Definition:** Merges all RTL modules into a single netlist.

* **Flow:** `flatten` command in Yosys removes hierarchy.

* **Advantages:**

  * Global optimizations across modules.  
  * Simpler netlist for some downstream tools.

* **Disadvantages:**

  * More runtime and memory use.  
  * Harder debugging (no module references).

## **‚è±Ô∏è Flip-Flop Coding Styles**

Flip-flops are the fundamental sequential elements in digital circuits. Below are clean RTL styles:

### **1\. Asynchronous Reset D Flip-Flop**

module dff\_asyncres (input clk, input async\_reset, input d, output reg q);  
  always @ (posedge clk, posedge async\_reset)  
    if (async\_reset)  
      q \<= 1'b0;  
    else  
      q \<= d;  
endmodule

Reset **immediately overrides clock** ‚Üí q \= 0\.

**2\. Asynchronous Set D Flip-Flop**

module dff\_async\_set (input clk, input async\_set, input d, output reg q);  
  always @ (posedge clk, posedge async\_set)  
    if (async\_set)  
      q \<= 1'b1;  
    else  
      q \<= d;  
endmodule

**3\. Synchronous Reset D Flip-Flop**

module dff\_syncres (input clk, input sync\_reset, input d, output reg q);  
  always @ (posedge clk)  
    if (sync\_reset)  
      q \<= 1'b0;  
    else  
      q \<= d;  
endmodule

Reset only applied **on clock edge**.
